item.title: Cats don't just hear "better" than us; they hear a completely different world of sound.
item.description: Human Range: We generally top out around 20 kHz. • Dog Range: They reach about 45 kHz. • Cat Range: They can hear up to roughly 64 kHz. 1. The 32 Ear Muscles While humans have a measly 6 muscles in their external ears (and most of us can’t even use them to wiggle), a cat has 32 individual muscles in each ear. • 180-Degree Rotation: They can rotate their ears independently to pinpoint the exact source of a sound without even moving their heads.  • The "Radar" Effect: They can curve and adjust the shape of the ear pinna (the outer part) to funnel sound waves more efficiently. Why the "Superpower"? This evolved because their primary prey—small rodents like mice and voles—communicate and scurry using ultra-high-frequency squeaks. If a cat couldn't hear those high pitches, they’d miss dinner. Fun Fact: Because their hearing is so sensitive, everyday noises like a vacuum cleaner or a crinkling chip bag can sound like a jet engine to them!
